One of the most fundamental decisions to make when you are architecting a solution on Hadoop/cloud is determining how data will be stored in Hadoop.

Major considerations for Hadoop data storage include:
	1. File Format
	2. Commpression techniques


why we need different file formats?
	we want to save storage
	we want fast processing
	we want less time for our I/O operations.

As the data increases, the cost for storage and processing increases too.

The various Hadoop file formats have evolved as a way to ease these issues across a number of use cases.


There are lot of choices available on file formats.
	1. Faster read
	2. Faster write
	3. splittable ( In big data solutions we consider only splittable file formats )
	4. Schema evolution support
	5. Advanced compression 
	6. Most compatible platformat. ( like spark,hive)

All the file formats are divided into 2 broad category.
	1. Row based file format.
		The whole row (all columns) of data from the disk has to be read in memory even if you need only a few columns. Row-oriented storage is suitable for situations where the entire row of data needs to be processed simultaneously.
		Writing is fast.
		Reading is slow for subset of columns.
		Less compression.
		Ex. 1 vishvjit Data-Enginner, 2 jivan Angular, 3 pranali Pl/Sql, 4 sanchit data-Enginner


	2. column based file format.
		The entire file is divided in several columns of data, and each column of data stored together
		The column-oriented format makes it possible to skip unneeded columns when reading data, suitable for situations where only a small portion of the rows are needed.
		Reading is fast.
		Writting is slow.
		Better Compression.
		Ex.  1 2 3 4 , vishvjit jivan pranali sanchit, data-Enginner angular Pl/Sql data-enginner


	3. Text File Format
		CSV - Raw file
			Data is stored in a human readble from.
			Everything is stored in a text from.
			ex. Interger value is also stored as text.
		Consume more storage.
		processing text file is very slow.
		IO operation will also take lot of time.
				Ex. conversion of string to interger. '444424' --> 444424 I/O operation takes lots of time.
		Human readable.


	XML & JSON
	==========
		Disadvantage of XML & JSON
		These are human readable.
		These takes lots of size due to everthing stored as string.
		processing on text file can be very very slow. Ex. conversion of string to interger. '444424' --> 444424
		I/O operation takes lots of time.
		These files are not spittable.


